Thanks for the thorough write-up and the Chris Brumme reference — this is a real and well-documented .NET runtime behavior.

Code investigation confirms the scope: only 14 `GC.KeepAlive` calls exist across 910+ P/Invoke call sites in the binding layer. The existing calls (in `SKSurface.ReadPixels`, `SKData.Create`, `SKImage`, `SKFontStyleSet`, `SKBitmap`, `SKTextBlob`) were added in PR #1258 (2020) but only for a handful of "this" and pixel-data cases.

PR #3394 is open with an initial pass at adding `GC.KeepAlive` calls. The key question is whether it covers all call sites and whether the code generator (`utils/generate.ps1`) should be extended to emit these automatically for future APIs.

In the interim, callers can add `GC.KeepAlive()` after SkiaSharp method calls where the managed object might not be referenced afterward:

```csharp
canvas.DrawPicture(picture);
GC.KeepAlive(picture);
GC.KeepAlive(canvas);
```
